### Pointers with Functions

Pointer parameters allow functions to modify caller variables.

### Pass by Pointer

```go
func increment(x *int) {
    *x++
}

func main() {
    n := 10
    increment(&n)
    fmt.Println(n) // 11
}
```

### Returning Pointers

```go
func newInt(x int) *int {
    result := x * 2
    return &result // safe: Go allocates on heap if needed
}

func main() {
    p := newInt(21)
    fmt.Println(*p) // 42
}
```

### Pointer to Large Structs

Passing a pointer to a large struct is more efficient:

```go
type LargeStruct struct {
    data [1000]int
}

// Efficient: passes 8 bytes (pointer)
func process(p *LargeStruct) {
    p.data[0] = 42
}

// Inefficient: copies entire 8000 bytes
func processCopy(s LargeStruct) LargeStruct {
    s.data[0] = 42
    return s
}
```

### Method Receivers

Pointer receivers can modify the struct:

```go
type Counter struct {
    Value int
}

func (c *Counter) Increment() {
    c.Value++ // modifies the original
}

func (c Counter) ValueOnly() int {
    return c.Value // read-only, copy
}
```

### Slice vs Pointer to Slice

```go
// Passing a slice (header copy) - usually sufficient
func modifyFirst(s []int) {
    if len(s) > 0 {
        s[0] = 99 // visible to caller
    }
}

// Passing pointer to slice - needed if reallocating
func appendItem(s *[]int, val int) {
    *s = append(*s, val) // visible to caller
}
```

> **Key Point:** Use pointer parameters when you need to modify the original value or avoid copying large data. For small values like ints, prefer value semantics.

codeExample:
package main

import "fmt"

func swap(a, b *int) {
    *a, *b = *b, *a
}

func double(x *int) {
    *x *= 2
}

func main() {
    x, y := 10, 20
    fmt.Println("before:", x, y)
    swap(&x, &y)
    fmt.Println("after swap:", x, y)

    double(&x)
    fmt.Println("after double:", x, y)
}
